Officials of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC) have detained the Clerk of the Ondo State House of Assembly, Mr. Bode Aladeyelu and two other civil servants. The anti-graft body is investigating alleged fraud in the Assembly involving N2.4million, which was released to enable the Clerk and two others attend a two-day seminar organised by the National Productivity Centre, Lagos.It was alleged that those who collected the money never attended the seminar. The Clerk and the two workers were said to have honoured the EFCC invitation, but they were detained at the weekend. Spokesman for the Assembly Mr. Gbenga Omole declined to comment on the matter. “I am not answering any question. I am going to address the press tomorrow (today),” he said. The Nation By Moji Eniola Ikeja - An Ikeja High Court will on April 18 rule on the admissibility of a report by the Department of State Services (DSS) to the Senate on Mr Ibrahim Magu, the Acting Chairman of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC). The News Agency of Nigeria… In "News" LAGOS - A witness, Mr Adewale Olatunji, on Friday told a Federal High Court in  Lagos  that the conferences attended by the members of the Lagos State House of Assembly (LAHA) were based on approval. Olatunji, a former Clerk of the Assembly, was giving evidence at the resumed trial of… In "News" • EFCC Acting Chairman, Ibrahim Magu ABUJA - After securing the conviction of former Abia State governor, Orji Uzor Kalu, the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC) has stepped up the investigation of three incumbent governors and eight others who have completed their tenures. The sitting governors under investigation by… In "Top Stories"